		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Imagine how much the sprites in <em>Tales of Phantasia</em> would flicker (they already flicker on the SNES sometimes, wich allows 4 times more sprites per line than the NES).</div><br />Sure, but I think it's still cool to simulate the existence of ports that never came to be. It's a complete waste of time, of course, so I don't do that anymore.<br /><br />NOTE: It may be weird that I say that while using my current avatar, but hopefully, those are not just graphics and I will complete my Sonic game.</div>
<br />Ha, I'd love to see that. Somari was a neat achievement, but it doesn't really stack up to either the NES SMB games or the Sonic games. (SMW for NES, though...wow. Just wow.)
<br />
<br />Clay Man, 8-bit color, unless the software you're using was designed to run in 8-bit color, just amounts to crappy dithering and piss-poor palette selection.
<br />
<br />I did write something like this once - it converted a 320x200 24-bit raw bitmap into a C= 64 multicolor mode picture (without dithering, just nearest-match color,) but it was quite buggy (it didn't pick colors very well and splattered green all over everything where there wasn't any green to begin with.) One of these days I'll get it whipped into shape...

		

